---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;

// Read the master report markdown for table of contents generation
const toc = [
  { id: 'classification', label: 'I — Classification Framework' },
  { id: 'probe', label: 'II — Entropy-Collapse Probe' },
  { id: 'atlas', label: 'III — HeadGenome Atlas' },
  { id: 'causal', label: 'IV — Causal Ablation' },
  { id: 'universality', label: 'V–VII — Universality Proofs' },
  { id: 'semantics', label: 'VIII — Semantic Anatomy' },
  { id: 'speedup', label: 'IX — Speedup Analysis' },
  { id: 'geometry', label: 'X — KV Cache Geometry' },
  { id: 'discussion', label: 'XI — Discussion & Future Work' },
];
---
<Layout title="Full Report" description="The HeadGenome Master Report — all sections, figures, and analysis.">
<div class="page-top">
  <p class="eyebrow">06 — Full Report</p>
  <h1>HeadGenome<br/>Master Report</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    The complete technical write-up — all phases, figures, and quantitative results.
    Use the table of contents to navigate or scroll through in sequence.
  </p>
  <div class="report-actions">
    <a href="https://github.com/skhavin/attentionheadgenome/blob/master/outputs/final_artifacts/HeadGenome_Master_Report.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="report-action-link">
      View on GitHub ↗
    </a>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="report-layout">
  <!-- TOC sidebar -->
  <aside class="report-toc">
    <p class="toc-title">Contents</p>
    <nav>
      {toc.map(t => (
        <a href={`#${t.id}`} class="toc-link">{t.label}</a>
      ))}
    </nav>
  </aside>

  <!-- Report content -->
  <article class="report-body">

    <section id="classification" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part I — Classification Framework</h2>
      <p>
        The HeadGenome framework classifies every attention head in a trained transformer into
        one of four functional types using a two-dimensional probe: the V/Q norm ratio
        (‖W_V‖/‖W_Q‖) and the entropy-collapse score under structured and semantic stress tests.
        No supervised labels are used. The probe is applied after training — it reads out the
        functional specialisation that gradient descent has already encoded into the weights.
      </p>
      <h3>The four classes</h3>
      <div class="type-grid">
        {[
          { cls: 'sink',      name: 'Sink',      desc: 'Absorbs residual attention mass onto punctuation and the BOS token. Structurally inert. Does not participate in semantic routing. Characterised by extremely high entropy-collapse score on punctuation-heavy sequences and low V/Q ratio.' },
          { cls: 'local',     name: 'Local',     desc: 'Attends within a sliding window of nearby tokens. Encodes positional context rather than semantic content. The majority class — 81–86% of all heads across all architectures. Characterised by moderate entropy and low V/Q ratio.' },
          { cls: 'retrieval', name: 'Retrieval', desc: 'Performs long-range semantic retrieval. Reaches to semantically relevant tokens anywhere in the context window. Characterised by high V/Q ratio (value-dominated) and sharp entropy-collapse on semantic repeat sequences.' },
          { cls: 'induction', name: 'Induction', desc: 'Copies retrieved content from the Retrieval circuit into the residual stream. Cannot function without Retrieval heads providing the source signal. Characterised by highest entropy-collapse scores on induction-pattern sequences.' },
        ].map(t => (
          <div class="type-entry">
            <span class={`pill pill-${t.cls}`}>{t.name}</span>
            <p>{t.desc}</p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="probe" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part II — Entropy-Collapse Probe</h2>
      <p>
        The entropy-collapse probe runs 200 prompts through the model and records the
        entropy of each head's attention distribution. Four prompt families are used:
        local-window sequences, semantic-repeat sequences, induction-pattern sequences,
        and punctuation-heavy sequences. The probe score for each head is the degree
        to which entropy collapses below the uniform baseline on the matching prompt family.
      </p>
      <p>
        The V/Q ratio is computed from the frozen weight matrices W_V and W_Q:
        δ = ‖W_V‖_F / ‖W_Q‖_F. This is a weight-space property requiring no forward pass.
        Together, (entropy-collapse, δ) form a 2D embedding in which the four classes
        naturally cluster without any supervised separation.
      </p>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig1_vq_scaling.png`} alt="V/Q scaling law" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 1 — V/Q ratio vs. relative depth. The monotonic scaling law holds across all four architectures with p ≈ 1.92 × 10⁻¹²⁷.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="atlas" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part III — The HeadGenome Atlas</h2>
      <p>
        Projecting all 1,568 heads onto the (δ, entropy) plane produces the HeadGenome Atlas —
        a 2D map in which the four classes occupy non-overlapping, reproducible regions.
        The Atlas is not a visualisation of the probe; it is the probe output. The separation
        is geometric, not aesthetic.
      </p>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/atlas.png`} alt="HeadGenome atlas" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 3 — The HeadGenome Atlas. 1,568 heads, coloured by class. GPT-2 Medium (MHA), Qwen-0.5B, Qwen-1.5B, and Llama-3.2-1B (GQA).</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig2_bifurcation.png`} alt="Bifurcation axis" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 2 — The bifurcation axis. Retrieval and Induction heads peel away from the Local trajectory at ~40–60% depth.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="causal" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part IV — Causal Ablation</h2>
      <p>
        To verify that the taxonomy captures genuine functional differences (not just
        statistical correlations), we perform causal ablation: we zero-out the attention
        weights of each head class during inference and measure the recovery rate on
        a suite of long-range recall tasks.
      </p>
      <div class="ablation-results">
        <div class="abl-row">
          <span class="abl-condition">Retrieval ablated only</span>
          <span class="abl-result abl-fail">0% recovery</span>
        </div>
        <div class="abl-row">
          <span class="abl-condition">Induction ablated only</span>
          <span class="abl-result abl-fail">0% recovery</span>
        </div>
        <div class="abl-row">
          <span class="abl-condition">Both ablated together</span>
          <span class="abl-result abl-pass">96.5% recovery</span>
        </div>
        <div class="abl-row">
          <span class="abl-condition">Local ablated</span>
          <span class="abl-result">Positional degradation only</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p>
        The 96.5% recovery when both are co-ablated is consistent with a residual stream that
        was never contaminated by the circuit — the information flow is cleanly removed.
        The 0% recovery when ablating either class alone proves a functional dependency:
        the two classes form a single co-dependent circuit.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The Perplexity Illusion.</strong> Models maintain near-perfect perplexity
        (&lt;0.1 nat degradation) after ablating all Retrieval heads — while losing all ability
        to answer questions requiring long-range recall. Standard evaluation metrics are blind
        to this failure mode.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="universality" class="report-section">
      <h2>Parts V–VII — Universality Proofs</h2>
      <h3>Initialization Null (Figure 8)</h3>
      <p>
        A randomly-initialised GPT-2 shows no V/Q structure — flat, noisy, no monotonic
        trend. After training, the law emerges to p ≈ 10⁻¹²⁷. The structure is a product
        of gradient descent, not of the architecture's initialisation.
      </p>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig8_universality.png`} alt="Initialization null" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 8 — V/Q ratio in random-init GPT-2 (top) vs. trained GPT-2 (bottom).</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <h3>Permutation Null (Figure 9)</h3>
      <p>
        When models are fed randomly shuffled token sequences (destroying syntax and meaning),
        Induction heads show equal or greater entropy-collapse scores — they are structural
        pattern-copy detectors, not language detectors. Retrieval heads attenuate, confirming
        their semantic specificity. The four-class structure is recovered in its entirety.
      </p>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig9_permutation.png`} alt="Permutation null" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 9 — Entropy-collapse probe on natural vs. shuffled sequences.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <h3>Cross-Domain Proof (Figure 10)</h3>
      <p>
        GPT-2 (WebText), Qwen (multilingual), and Llama (instruction corpus) all obey the
        same V/Q scaling law with the same slope. The governing law is stable across radically
        different training distributions, model sizes, and attention mechanisms (MHA vs GQA).
      </p>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig10_crossdomain.png`} alt="Cross-domain proof" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 10 — V/Q scaling law overlaid across all four architectures.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="semantics" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part VIII — Semantic Anatomy</h2>
      <p>
        We audited the top attended vocabulary items for each head type on WikiText-103 using
        the full training distribution. The lexical anatomy confirms the entropy-collapse
        classification at the token level:
      </p>
      <ul class="report-list">
        <li><strong>Sink heads</strong> consistently direct the largest fraction of their attention mass toward punctuation tokens (commas, periods) and the BOS token.</li>
        <li><strong>Local heads</strong> attend uniformly to adjacent content words. No consistent lexical preference — position is the primary signal.</li>
        <li><strong>Retrieval heads</strong> show strong lexical specificity — high top-k concentration on semantically content-bearing tokens (proper nouns, entities, rare words).</li>
        <li><strong>Induction heads</strong> show the highest top-1 token dominance of any class — they attend almost exclusively to the token they are copying forward.</li>
      </ul>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig7_lexical.png`} alt="Lexical anatomy" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 7 — Top attended tokens by head type on WikiText-103.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="speedup" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part IX — Projected Speedup Analysis</h2>
      <p>
        Given fractions f_local, f_sink, f_critical summing to 1, and window size W:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        Sparse FLOPs = f_critical · N² + f_local · N · W + f_sink · N · (W + S)<br/>
        Speedup(N) → 1/f_critical as N → ∞
      </div>
      <p>
        The speedup grows monotonically with sequence length and converges to the
        critical-head ceiling 1/f_critical. At N=4K (typical long-document context),
        the 85% Local heads are already 4–4.4× cheaper than dense. At N=32K (full-book),
        Qwen-0.5B approaches its 8.3× ceiling.
      </p>
      <div class="reveal">
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Model</th><th>f_critical</th><th>Ceiling</th><th>N=4K</th><th>N=32K</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>GPT-2 Medium</td><td>15%</td><td>6.7×</td><td>3.9×</td><td>6.1×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Qwen-0.5B</td><td>12%</td><td>8.3×</td><td>4.4×</td><td>7.7×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Llama-3.2-1B</td><td>15%</td><td>6.7×</td><td>3.9×</td><td>6.1×</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Qwen-1.5B</td><td>14%</td><td>7.1×</td><td>4.0×</td><td>6.5×</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig11_speedup.png`} alt="Speedup curves" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 11 — Projected speedup curves vs. sequence length.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section id="geometry" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part X — KV Cache Geometry</h2>
      <p>
        By extracting the Key (K) vectors from past_key_values and projecting to 3D via PCA,
        we visually confirm the structural taxonomy. Each head type organises the same token
        sequence into a qualitatively distinct geometric manifold.
      </p>
      <ul class="report-list">
        <li><strong>Local heads:</strong> A continuous nearly-linear time-curve. Position encoded strictly sequentially; semantics absent.</li>
        <li><strong>Sink heads:</strong> Punctuation and BOS pushed far to the periphery; remaining tokens collapse into a tight isotropic ball.</li>
        <li><strong>Retrieval/Induction heads:</strong> Identical words cluster regardless of temporal position (all instances of "fox" collapse together).</li>
        <li><strong>Untrained control:</strong> Amorphous cloud — no positional, semantic, or identity structure. Falsifies the null hypothesis.</li>
      </ul>
      <figure class="figure">
        <img src={`${base}/figures/fig12_geometry.png`} alt="KV geometry" loading="lazy" />
        <figcaption>Figure 12 — 3D PCA projection of KV-cache Key vectors for the four reference heads + untrained control. GPT-2 Medium, canonical reference heads from Figures 1–2.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <p>
        The untrained control is the critical control: it falsifies the null hypothesis that random
        high-dimensional vectors could accidentally appear structured under PCA.
        The geometry is emergent from training, not from the architecture or projection method.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="discussion" class="report-section">
      <h2>Part XI — Discussion & Future Work</h2>
      <h3>Semantic Drift and Localized Plasticity</h3>
      <p>
        The taxonomy models functional regions as a stable manifold, but ~5–10% of critical heads
        exhibit Semantic Drift: sliding between the Local precursor state and specialised
        bifurcation branches depending on the structural entropy of the input. A refined taxonomy
        may need a dynamic, context-dependent component for these heads.
      </p>
      <h3>Open Questions</h3>
      <ul class="report-list">
        <li>Does the four-class structure hold at 7B, 70B, and 400B parameter scale?</li>
        <li>Do hyper-diagonal heads warrant a fifth class, or are they a developmental transition state?</li>
        <li>Can FlexAttention realise the projected FLOP savings with a hardware-native sparse kernel?</li>
        <li>Does the taxonomy transfer to Mamba, RWKV, or other non-attention sequence models?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

  </article>
</div>

</Layout>

<style>
.report-actions { margin-top: 2rem; }
.report-action-link {
  color: var(--accent); text-decoration: none; font-size: .9rem; font-weight: 400;
  transition: opacity .2s;
}
.report-action-link:hover { opacity: .7; }

.report-layout {
  max-width: 1100px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 0 2.5rem 8rem;
  display: grid; grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr; gap: 5rem; align-items: start;
}
@media (max-width: 860px) {
  .report-layout { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 2rem; }
  .report-toc { display: none; }
}

.report-toc { position: sticky; top: 5rem; }
.toc-title {
  font-size: .65rem; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: .1em; text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--text-3); margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
.toc-link {
  display: block; font-size: .8rem; font-weight: 300; color: var(--text-3);
  text-decoration: none; padding: .3rem 0; transition: color .2s;
  border-left: 1px solid var(--border); padding-left: 1rem; margin-bottom: .1rem;
}
.toc-link:hover { color: var(--text); border-left-color: var(--accent); }

.report-body { min-width: 0; }
.report-section {
  padding: 4rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
}
.report-section:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
.report-section h2 {
  font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.5vw, 2rem);
  font-weight: 200; letter-spacing: -.04em; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.2;
}
.report-section h3 {
  font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 500; letter-spacing: -.01em;
  margin: 2.5rem 0 .75rem; color: var(--text);
}
.report-section p {
  font-size: .93rem; color: var(--text-2); font-weight: 300;
  line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
}
.report-section strong { font-weight: 500; color: var(--text); }
.report-list {
  margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem 1.2rem;
  display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: .6rem;
}
.report-list li {
  font-size: .92rem; color: var(--text-2); font-weight: 300; line-height: 1.65;
}

.type-grid { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
.type-entry { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: .4rem; }
.type-entry p { font-size: .88rem; color: var(--text-2); font-weight: 300; line-height: 1.6; margin: 0; }

.ablation-results { margin: 1.5rem 0; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
.abl-row {
  display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center;
  padding: .9rem 0; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  font-size: .9rem;
}
.abl-condition { color: var(--text-2); font-weight: 300; }
.abl-result { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: .85rem; font-weight: 500; color: var(--text-3); }
.abl-fail { color: var(--sink); }
.abl-pass { color: var(--retrieval); }

.formula-block {
  background: var(--bg2); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); border: 1px solid var(--border);
  padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem; font-family: var(--mono); font-size: .82rem;
  color: var(--text-2); line-height: 2; margin: 1.5rem 0;
}
</style>
